RT @mdkpage: @AaronHyndman The candidate isn’t a “figurehead”. They’re a leader of that movement. But they also need support + an inclusive…
RT @mdkpage: @AaronHyndman New Jersey needs an actual progressive movement and an actual investment to defeat the line. Not orgs that claim…
I have news: a savior is not coming. We’re going to have to collectively save ourselves

Realistically it takes a multi-pronged effort and even the wins of Obama, Bernie, and AOC came after years of groundwork beforehand. 

I understand this tweet was said with respect but I implore you to study more deeply how successful movements actually come about.

One of the reasons we keep losing is because we think there is going to be one savior to do it all & that simply is unrealistic & again doesn’t match up with history. 

It’s also why people get frustrated w/ the Obama’s, Bernie’s, and AOCs of the world when they can do magic (3)

And typically towards the end one or two people are crowned as “leaders of the movement” when in reality it took many forms of movement strategies to get something across the finish line. 

This is true of the civil rights movement as well as movements for independence (2/)

I respect your point of view. Also, what you’re describing above does not match up with how movements are won throughout history despite the fact that history books teach it this way.

Movements are typically won after years sometimes generations of grassroots organizing (1/) https://t.co/T63OuInF0i

But for anyone who is interested the $2 mill number is about what it will cost for your overhead, congressional campaign things like mailers, ads, etc. and then the same for the issue campaign aspect. 

Thanks! Hit the DMs or my number if you have questions.

Like I said this is the last that I’m going to say on it because having the narrative that the ballot line is impossible to beat serves the interests of those who aren’t here for community work and they will fight tooth and nail to not do that work (5/)

So candidates are then tasks with raising at least two million while simultaneously not receiving help to achieve that number because of the self fulfilling narrative that the ballot line is impossible to beat (4/)

In an ideal world grassroots orgs would actually be doing the ground work in between elections to do voter education but that doesn’t happen in NJ and the majority of the “organizing” is top heavy. 

Thus the entire job is left to candidates during their run (3/)

There are two things that are very expensive to do: run for congress (at least a mill) and run issue campaigns (can cost millions) 

When you run in NJ you have to do both at the same time because you have to get people to vote for you AND teach them HOW to vote for you (2/)

What’s up folks! 

So I know I’m not going to be believed here because the ppl have their narratives for their reasons so I’m only going to say this once and only once so it’s on record: the ballot line is not nearly as large a hindrance as money in winning elections in NJ (🧵)
